# Section 9 Exercises {#sec-exercises}

```{r echo=FALSE}
# customer_data already created in setup chunk
```

## Exercise 1 — Broom Practice {#sec-ex1}

> **Using the `customer_data` dataset (before splitting), fit a linear
> regression predicting `monthly_spend` from `tenure`, `num_products`,
> and `region`. Use `tidy()`, `glance()`, and `augment()` + ggplot2.**

```{r ex1-fit}
spend_fit <- lm(monthly_spend ~ tenure + num_products + region,
                data = customer_data)
```

### Coefficients via `tidy()` {#sec-ex1-tidy}

```{r ex1-tidy}
tidy(spend_fit) |>
  mutate(significant = p.value < 0.05)
```

**Interpretation:** Predictors with $p < 0.05$ are statistically
significant at the 5% level. Based on how the data were generated,
`tenure` and `num_products` should be significant positive predictors.
The `region` dummy variables (reference = East by default in R) reflect
whether region membership shifts the intercept; given that region was
not used to generate `monthly_spend` in this dataset, those coefficients
are likely not significant.

### Model Fit via `glance()` {#sec-ex1-glance}

```{r ex1-glance}
glance(spend_fit)
```

**Interpretation:** An $R^2$ near the value implied by the
data-generating process (tenure and num_products together explain most
of the signal) indicates a good fit. The F-test p-value well below 0.05
confirms the overall model is significant.

### Residual Plot via `augment()` {#sec-ex1-resid}

```{r ex1-resid, fig.cap="Residuals vs. Fitted Values — ideally scattered randomly around zero with no pattern."}
augment(spend_fit) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.4, color = "#5C6B73") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "#C05746", linewidth = 0.8) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, color = "#3B7DD8", linewidth = 0.8) +
  labs(
    title = "Residuals vs. Fitted Values",
    subtitle = "monthly_spend ~ tenure + num_products + region",
    x = "Fitted Values",
    y = "Residuals"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 13)
```

**Interpretation:** If the points scatter randomly around zero with no
discernible curve or fan shape, the linearity and homoscedasticity
assumptions are reasonably satisfied. A smooth trend line near zero
throughout supports this conclusion.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Exercise 2 — Data Splitting {#sec-ex2}

> **Create a 70/30 stratified split on `churn`. Verify churn rate
> similarity. Check `last_login_days` distribution.**

### Create the Split {#sec-ex2-split}

```{r ex2-split}
set.seed(123)
churn_split <- initial_split(customer_data, prop = 0.70, strata = churn)
churn_train <- training(churn_split)
churn_test  <- testing(churn_split)

cat("Training rows:", nrow(churn_train), "\n")
cat("Testing rows: ", nrow(churn_test),  "\n")
```

### Verify Churn Rate {#sec-ex2-churnrate}

```{r ex2-churnrate}
bind_rows(
  churn_train |> count(churn) |> mutate(set = "Training", pct = n / sum(n)),
  churn_test  |> count(churn) |> mutate(set = "Testing",  pct = n / sum(n))
) |>
  select(set, churn, n, pct) |>
  arrange(set, churn)
```

**Interpretation:** Stratified splitting ensures the churn rate is
nearly identical in both sets, preventing the training set from being
artificially "easier" or harder than the test set.

### Last Login Days Distribution {#sec-ex2-logindays}

```{r ex2-logindays, fig.cap="Overlapping density curves for last_login_days in training vs. test sets."}
bind_rows(
  churn_train |> mutate(set = "Training"),
  churn_test  |> mutate(set = "Testing")
) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = last_login_days, fill = set)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Training" = "#3B7DD8", "Testing" = "#C05746")) +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of last_login_days",
    subtitle = "Training vs. Testing sets",
    x = "Days Since Last Login",
    y = "Density",
    fill = "Set"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 13)
```

**Interpretation:** The two curves should closely overlap, confirming
that the split did not accidentally concentrate long-dormant customers
in one set.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Exercise 3 — Critical Thinking {#sec-ex3}

### Peeking at the Test Set {#sec-ex3-q1}

> *"I looked at the test set to understand the data better before
> modeling. I did not fit any models on it." Is this a problem?*

Yes, this is a problem — even without fitting models. When a modeler
examines the test set, they gain intuitions about its distribution,
outliers, and patterns that inevitably (and often unconsciously)
influence their feature engineering and modeling choices. This is called
**data leakage**, and it inflates optimism about how well the final
model will generalize. The test set should remain a sealed envelope
until the very last evaluation step.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Stratified Splitting for Fraud Detection {#sec-ex3-q2}

> *Only 0.1% of transactions are fraudulent. Why is stratified splitting
> especially important here?*

With such extreme class imbalance, a random split could place all or
nearly all fraud cases in one partition by chance alone. If the training
set contains no (or almost no) fraud examples, the model cannot learn
what fraud looks like. Stratified splitting guarantees that both the
training and test sets contain the same proportion of fraudulent
transactions (≈ 0.1%), ensuring the model learns from genuine positive
cases and that test-set performance reflects real-world conditions.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### High Training Accuracy, Low Test Accuracy {#sec-ex3-q3}

> *A model achieves 92% training accuracy and 61% test accuracy. What
> does this tell you?*

The large gap (31 percentage points) is a classic sign of
**overfitting** — the model has memorized the training data, including
its noise, rather than learning generalizable patterns. Next steps would
include: (1) applying regularization (L1/L2), (2) pruning model
complexity (fewer features, shallower trees), (3) using cross-validation
instead of a single train/test split to get a more stable performance
estimate, and (4) collecting more training data if possible.

